The information superhighway is
turning into Easy Street for high school
and college students searching for an
A—quality term paper. This is due to an
explosion of websites that offer papers
for little or no cost.

Two of the more popular term
paper depositories, School Sucks and
the Evil House of Cheat, each reported
some 1.2 million visits since their sites
opened.

Houston—based Kenny Sahr, the
creator of School Sucks, began oﬂ°er—
ing papers free of charge online about
18 months ago. The popularity of the
site, he said, is due in a large part to col-
lege professors spreading information
about Sahr’s site to the media

“It made a crucial difference,” said
Sahr. “I expected the media to jump in
and educators to overreact.”

Despite the popularity of his site
and the free-for—the-taking term papers,
he said he is actually helping to bring
about a positive change in the educa-
tion system.

“Checks and balances are missing

— in teaching. Instead, you have tenure,”

he said. “It’s not our best and brightest
going into teaching; it’s our mediocre
and average. [Students] need this
[quality teachers].

“Most [college] teachers don’t
even have a minor in education,” Sahr
added.

Despite what many people think,
he said he doesn’t condone cheating
and plagiarism.

In statistics compiled by a usage-
tracking company contracted by
School Sucks, Duke University had the
highest number of students in terms of
students visiting School Sucks, accord-
ing to a November report.

The Rochester Institute of
Technology and Pennsylvania State
University ﬁlled the second and third
slots, respectively.

The University of Pittsburgh was
not listed among the top 10.

Educators from the University of
Pemrsylvania, California Institute of
Technology, and Oklahoma State
University who publicly criticized Sahr
and School Sucks on his website did
not retum requests for comment.

