Poet deals with being
  black but looking white

-On the first day of second
grade, Toi Denicotte was asked to
ﬁll out a personal history card for
her teacher. At the bottom of the
card, she saw two boxes with the
words “negro” and “white” next to
them.

She contemplated which one
to check, hesitating as long as she
could.

Finally, she checked “negro.”
And, in her book, she recognized
this as one of her ﬁrst encounters
with race.

“By the time I was in second
grade, I already knew that white
people had something special,
desirable, a world I wanted to
enter,” she wrote.

What she didn’t realize then
was that she could enter that
world, but it wouldn’t be as desir-
able to her as she once imagined.
She also didn’t realize that years
later, she would sit down and pull
this memory from the depths of
her mind to include in a best-se1l-
ing novel.

Denicotte is a poetry profes-
sor at Pitt and the author of the
recently published “The Black
Noteboo  which takes the read-
er through her life as a light-
skinned black American. The
book, acclaimed by the
Washington Post, recently won the
Black Caucus of the American
Library Association Literary
Award, one of the highest
American awards for black litera-
me. I
Denicotte said the book was
troubling to write because of the
hurt she suffered throughout her
life over her skin color. In the
book, she writes of her struggles
with herself and her family
because of her light skin.

“It’s very difficult to write
about it,” said Denicotte. “You
don’t want to remember certain
things.” I

In “Ihe Black Notebooks,”
which took over 20 years to write,
Denicotte draws a picture of her
life through individual stories and
how she overcame the guilt of
using her light skin to gain where
dark—skinned blacks could not.

“One of the advantages to
having light skin is that you’re
invisible in some places,” said
Denicotte. “I wanted to make
something beautiful out "of some-
thing ugly. That’s why the book
took so long to write.”

Derricotte said she even used

her light skin to “trick” people into
thinking she is white. As a result of
this, Denicotte sometimes felt
guilty and out of place.

For example, when looking
for homes in Upper Montclair,
N .Y., Denicotte would go alone to
the realtors, leaving her dark-
skinned husband at home, kr1ow—
ing she would be shown nicer, bet-
ter—p1iced homes when she was
alone. ,

She looked at 80 homes on
her own, and drove with her hus-
band at night to see the homes,
explaining to him what each room
looked like on the inside.

“I got a rage in me and a

desire to have one of those hous— y

es,” said Denicotte.

When Denicotte and her hus-
band Bruce ﬁnally decided on a
home in an upper-class, all-white
neighborhood, Denicotte realized
that the segregation she saw while
searching for a house did not cease
when they moved in.

The residents of the neighbor-
hood excluded Derricotte and her
family from a country club they all
belonged to. In the archaic rules of
the club, blacks were not allowed
to join.

The book and her introspect
into the problems she has encoun-
tered with race have given her a
tool to reach out to others, and her
high position as a professor at the
University of Pittsburgh puts her
in the best position to get through
to students.

In a break between traveling
to neighboring states to'do read-'
ings, Denicotte gave a reading of
her new book to Pitt students on
Thursday.

