With website names like "School Sucks" and
"Evil House of Cheat," it's hard to believe their
owners who offer used term papers online when
they say they're not trying to aid plagiarism. Few
students may look to other term papers for their
research or ideas. After all, how would you even
footnote that in your own essay?

But the owners do make a good point when
they suggest that giving students easy access to
these papers should pressure teachers to be more
creative in developing assignments.

Professors can combat plagiarism by making
it extremely difficult to accomplish.

Punishment for plagiarism will only work if
the culprits are caught, and then it is after the fact,
when somebody has already cheated himself and
his classmates by submitting another's work as his
own. As always, prevention is better than a cure.

Professors should work hard every semester to
develop new assignments and invent new, cre-
ative topics on which students can write term

' papers . .

Even with the thousands of papers online, the
odds are still slim of finding a good paper on the
history of criticism of ancient Egyptian poetry as
evidenced in Shakespeare's "Antony and
Cleopatra."

Of course, not every term paper topic needs to
be so obscure, but the more creative and focused
an assignment is, the more difficult plagiarism
will be and the more students will learn from the
exercise.

We pay a lot of money to come to college.
Many of us are going to leave here with debts
written in five figures. Most of us are smart
enough to write our own papers and try to get our
money's worth out of this education. But even for
us, we'd come a lot closer to that goal if our
teachers spent time devising new assignments
rather than recycling the same ones from last
semester or 20 years ago.

